   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1846_12_24_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName>
                  <date when="1846-12-24">Dec 24 1846</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Friend</persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               I <choice>
                  <orig>shd</orig>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice> not have<lb/>
               let others be before me in <choice>
                  <orig>men-<lb/>
               -tioning</orig>
                  <reg>mentioning</reg>
               </choice> my little woman's intended<lb/>
               wedding, but that at the time<lb/>
               when I found her romance near<lb/>
               its last chapter, I was afflicted<lb/>
               sadly by recurring reports of<lb/>
               evil <choice>
                  <orig>abot</orig>
                  <reg>about</reg>
               </choice> her uncle in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IN">India</placeName>
               <lb/>
               which indeed <hi rend="underline">for me</hi> made it<lb/>
               impossible <unclear>to enter</unclear> rightly at the<lb/>
               feelings of the younger generation.<lb/>
               Moreover I was then as I am<lb/>
               still in a poor uncomfortable<lb/>
               state of health myself - but of<lb/>
               that no more. And I know how<lb/>
               heartily you will rejoice that I can<lb/>
               now
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1846_12_24_page02.jpg"/>
              report favourably as this W. <unclear>Scott</unclear>
               <lb/>
              I had by last mail a letter from<lb/>
              himself dated 22<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> October. He<lb/>
              had removed on the 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> to the<lb/>
              home of a friend of his &amp; relation<lb/>
              &amp; namesake of mine some few<lb/>
              miles on the way <choice>
                  <orig>frm</orig>
                  <reg>from</reg>
               </choice>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Bangalore_IN">Bangalore</placeName>
               <lb/>
              to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Madras_IN">Madras</placeName>. During the intervening<lb/>
              days he had been sensibly<lb/>
              gathering strength &amp; he &amp; his wife<lb/>
              &amp; his host (whose letters also I<lb/>
              have seen) concurred in<lb/>
              thinking that he <choice>
                  <orig>w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>would</reg>
               </choice> speedily<lb/>
              be able to continue his journey<lb/>
              and embark for <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>. He<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>cd</orig>
                  <reg>could</reg>
               </choice> have no other chance but in<lb/>
              the sea voyage &amp; home of a<lb/>
              permanent care after a most<lb/>
              severe case of <unclear>abscess</unclear> in the<lb/>
              liver. I hope &amp; trust I shall<lb/>
              have him here anon &amp; that<lb/>
              his constitution may have<lb/>
              so rallied as <unclear>&amp;</unclear> to afford him<lb/>
              the prospect of a tranquil<lb/>
              Evening of life in the country.<lb/>
              That he <choice>
                  <orig>shd</orig>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice> be well enough<lb/>
              for active service, at least<lb/>
              for several years to come, my<lb/>
              medical friends assure me is<lb/>
              in the highest degree improbable.<lb/>
              Since you will not come to<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Londn</orig>
                     <reg>London</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> I must go to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
               <lb/>
              &amp; bye &amp; bye I am likely to be<lb/>
              a free <choice>
                  <orig>batchelor</orig>
                  <reg>bachelor</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1846_12_24_page03.jpg"/>
               Eugh! <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockW1">My son</persName> is daily expecting<lb/>
               to join his <choice>
                  <orig>regimt</orig>
                  <reg>regiment</reg>
               </choice> at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Canterbury_ENK">Canterbury</placeName>
               <lb/>
               &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockC1">Miss Charlotte</persName> will I suppose<lb/>
               be taken <choice>
                  <orig>fr</orig>
                  <reg>from</reg>
               </choice> me at Easter<lb/>
               or at latest in the Summer.<lb/>
               They are both now in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#STK">Scotland</placeName>
               <lb/>
               where had I been well <choice>
                  <orig>engh</orig>
                  <reg>enough</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               to travel I <choice>
                  <orig>shd</orig>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice> have been<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>w</orig>
                  <reg>with</reg>
               </choice> them at Chrs for line season<lb/>
               - but that over they will come<lb/>
               up without delay. They have<lb/>
               had a very happy Summer &amp;<lb/>
               Autum there &amp; <hi rend="underline">he</hi> may<lb/>
               not have the like again<lb/>
               for years to come.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1846_12_24_page04.jpg"/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockC1">Charlotte</persName> will be a terrible<lb/>
               loss to my fireside - but I<lb/>
               must consider how soon the<lb/>
               railway is to annihilate<lb/>
               distance - &amp; let any rate<lb/>
               I am not so silly as to<lb/>
               let my thoughts rest on anything<lb/>
               but the great comfort of<lb/>
               knowing that she is to be<lb/>
               provided <choice>
                  <orig>w</orig>
                  <reg>with</reg>
               </choice> a kind protector<lb/>
               of her own standing in place<lb/>
               of <add>a</add> worn &amp; weary papa<lb/>
               I think myself entitled<lb/>
               to count on <unclear>her</unclear> many chances<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1846_12_24_page05.jpg"/>
               as most fathers ought to<lb/>
               anticipate of a tranquil<lb/>
               &amp; happy lot for my<lb/>
               child: &amp; the residence of<lb/>
               her <hi rend="underline">promisso</hi> is within<lb/>
               15 miles of my brother's<lb/>
               place, so that in days to<lb/>
               come her <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockW1">brother</persName> &amp; she<lb/>
               are likely to be my neighbours<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I know well that you<lb/>
               <unclear>have had</unclear> Sad new<lb/>
               affliction - but nothing<lb/>
               1846 De<hi rend="superscript">f</hi>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">Mr Lockhart</persName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_936_1846_12_24_page06.jpg"/>
               can ever render you indifferent<lb/>
               to either the good or the evil<lb/>
               that <choice>
                  <orig>befals</orig>
                  <reg>befalls</reg>
               </choice> a friend - I<lb/>
               hope <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Mrs Wilson</persName> when<lb/>
               she must leave you<lb/>
               is to bring me some<lb/>
               comfortable tidings<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <unclear/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>yrs</orig>
                  <reg>yours</reg>
               </choice>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">
                  <hi rend="underline">J G Lockhart</hi>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     1846<lb/>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LockJ1">Lockhart</persName>
                     <lb/>
                  </addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
